# Fix macOS SIGKILL During Delta Upgrade

## Problem

Running `sentry cli upgrade` on macOS with the delta upgrade system causes
the process to be killed with SIGKILL. The shell reports `killed` with no
error message. On Linux, the same operation works fine.

## Root Cause

The delta upgrade system in `src/lib/bspatch.ts` uses `Bun.mmap(oldPath)`
to memory-map the currently running binary for reading during patch
application. `Bun.mmap()` always requests `PROT_WRITE` in its C/zig
implementation regardless of the `shared` flag.

On macOS, the kernel's **AMFI** (Apple Mobile File Integrity) code signing
enforcement sends an uncatchable `SIGKILL` for ANY writable mapping —
both `MAP_SHARED` and `MAP_PRIVATE` — on code-signed Mach-O binaries.
All Bun-compiled binaries have ad-hoc code signatures.

An initial fix (PR #339) changed `Bun.mmap()` to use `{ shared: false }`
(MAP_PRIVATE), but this was **insufficient** because MAP_PRIVATE with
PROT_WRITE is also rejected by macOS AMFI.

### Evidence from Sentry telemetry

- **Zero** successful macOS upgrade traces from delta-enabled versions
- **All 4** successful delta upgrade traces were from Ubuntu Linux
- **26** successful macOS upgrade traces from pre-delta versions (full download)
- The orphaned DB span at 18:34 UTC from the killed version confirms an
  upgrade was attempted but the process was killed before telemetry flushed

### Call chain

```
upgrade.ts       → attemptDeltaUpgrade(version, process.execPath, destPath)
delta-upgrade.ts → applyPatchChain(chain, oldBinaryPath, destPath)
bspatch.ts       → Bun.mmap(oldPath)  ← SIGKILL on macOS
```

## Fix

### `src/lib/bspatch.ts` — platform-conditional old file loading

```typescript
const oldFile =
  process.platform === "darwin"
    ? new Uint8Array(await Bun.file(oldPath).arrayBuffer())
    : Bun.mmap(oldPath);
```

- **macOS**: Read into memory via `arrayBuffer()` (~100 MB heap, freed after
  patching). Avoids mmap entirely — no kernel code signing checks.
- **Linux**: Keep zero-heap `Bun.mmap()` — ELF binaries have no such restriction.

## Testing

Existing tests pass since fixtures are plain binary files (not signed Mach-O).
The SIGKILL is an OS-level kernel behavior only reproducible on macOS with a
code-signed binary. No new tests needed — the fix is a platform check with
well-understood semantics.
